\begin_layout Standard
Lets define a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

measure–preserving finite automaton
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This will be inadequate for the agent model,
 but is one of the central concepts,
 so lets start.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=\left\{ a_{k}:k\in1,\cdots,N\right\} $
\end_inset

 a finite set of symbols,
 the input alphabet.
 (I guess it could be countable:
 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\omega$
\end_inset

 or maybe larger,
 bt for now just,
 uhh,
 countable?)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left(X,\mathcal{B},\mu\right)$
\end_inset

 be space with a Borel algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 and a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\mathcal{B}\to\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=\left\{ T_{k}:k\in1,\cdots,N\right\} $
\end_inset

 be a collection of transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}:X\to X$
\end_inset

 that are measure–preserving 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(T_{k}^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)=\mu\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $N=1$
\end_inset

 this corresponds to the standard definition of a dynamical system.
 When there is only one 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

,
 it is interpreted as the forward–time evolution of the system.
 But here,
 it is curiously different.
 One possible interpretation is that there are 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 different time axes.
 But this is bunkum,
 since we will soon impose the requirement that for each time step,
 one and only one 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}$
\end_inset

 must be chosen.
 This implies an interpretation that there are many possible futures ahead of us.
 The selection of just one 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the selection of one possible future,
 and mapping it into the present (here and now).
 Huh.
 Well,
 I think I just got lucky,
 here,
 because I wasn't planning this in advance.
 Again,
 the universe sings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So,
 now,
 we mention that this can be specialized to multiple common cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $X=S=\left\{ s_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 a finite set of states,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 the counting measure,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=\delta$
\end_inset

 the transition function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta:S\times\Sigma\to S$
\end_inset

 one gets the bog–standard finite state machine.
 (Not yet a transducer,
 as there is no output,
 so Moore and Mealey do not yet enter the discussion.) If we set it up so that the initial state is 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}$
\end_inset

 then the measure is irrelevant,
 as the state transition function guarantees that the machine is always in just one and only one state at a time.
 A probabilistic state machine can be defined by having multiple initial states,
 and then purpose of the measure is to make sure we don't get too many (or too few) of them as the system progresses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

–simplex,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}:\Delta^{n}\to\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

 a Markov chain,
 one get a probabilistic finite automaton.
 If the starting point is a single point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta^{n}$
\end_inset

,
 then the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is once again irrelevant,
 as the Markov chain again guarantees that the machine is only in one state.
 Contacting with conventional notation,
 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\left(p_{1},\cdots,p_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 a vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 real numbers,
 interpreted as probabilities:
 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\sum_{i}p_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 There's awkwardness in contacting with the conventional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Pr}\left(X=X_{j}\right)$
\end_inset

 notation for Markov chains,
 since that notation requires a distinct random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j}$
\end_inset

 for each time–step 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and so the convention of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random variables
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is awkward in the present setting.
 It can be done,
 but I see no point in trying to make contact with that notation.
 It just would be a wall of text that doesn't clarify anything.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{C}P^{n}$
\end_inset

 complex projective space,
 or,
 alternately,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X=H$
\end_inset

 a Hilbert space,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}=U_{k}:H\to H$
\end_inset

 a set of unitary transformations,
 one gets a quantum finite automaton.
 A single point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\left|\psi\right\rangle \in X$
\end_inset

 is interpreted as a pure state.
 A mixed state is then a collection of points in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

;
 when this collection is uncountable,
 the Borel algebra and the measure is employed,
 so as to make the application of the unitary transforms meaningful.
 The quantum finite automaton is exactly the same thing as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

computer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

quantum computing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and there is a vast ocean of notation and conventions for talking about this.
 I don't see much point in articulating these at this time,
 other than to mention that the 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}$
\end_inset

 would correspond to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gates
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of various sorts,
 and the measure here becomes the Bures measure (Fubini–Study metric for mixed states).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It might be interesting to generalize from 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{C}P^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 some (complex) variety,
 or even a scheme,
 but I don't see the point of this just right now.
 This is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

varietal state machine
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 a homogeneous space (viz.
 quotient of Lie groups) and the 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}$
\end_inset

 being transformations on this homogeneous space,
 one gets the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

geometric state machine
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Again,
 this could be interesting,
 but I don't see any utility just right now.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The point of the above was rather trite:
 by using notation for measure–preserving dynamical systems,
 we can cover both the classical and the quantum cases at the same time,
 instead of having to have distinct conversations about each.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
OK,
 so that's the base tool.
 Now for some issues.
 If we are to describe an agent,
 then an assortment of issues arise.
 First,
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

input alphabet
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as the alphabet of sensory input from the external environment.
 However,
 by making it discrete,
 finite,
 we've forced the sensor to convert observations of the unbounded,
 uncountable external world into a finite set of discrete signals.
 This is OK for the perception of text,
 and maybe even OK for the perception of phonetic speech,
 but it's problematic for music,
 and certainly for vision.
 I mean,
 both can be pixelated,
 but that's hacky.
 It's more confusing if the external world is itself quantum,
 and so,
 instead of sensing a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

single thing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from the external world,
 the agent needs to sense a superposition in the external world.
 The algebraic language given above is inadequate for that.
 So,
 fixing this is a TODO item.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 for an agent with free will,
 the alphabet 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 needs to be split into 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{s}$
\end_inset

 coming from sensor 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{c}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the menu of choices available at any given time.
 The stream of events 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{s}$
\end_inset

 is fully deterministic:
 it is whatever the external world is raining down upon the sensors of the agent.
 The set of choices 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{c}$
\end_inset

 is internal and context–dependent:
 a choice I had yesterday may no longer be available today;
 new choices may open up tomorrow.
 The notation is inappropriate.
 Then,
 as before,
 choice is itself problematic,
 as how does the agent 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

choose
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

?
 If the idea of a supernatural spirit making a choice is to be avoided,
 then the choice needs to be reframed as a system on the edge of criticality.
 If we do want to allow supernatural spirits or oracles making decisions,
 then we have to articulate algebra for for how these work:
 an algebra of the supernatural.
 It might be OK to do this,
 simply in the name of distinguishing structural elements,
 but I see no need for this right now.
 Wishing to have a supernatural description just make things harder,
 it seems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A different issue is whether the Cartesian or the tensor product should be used.
 That is,
 should the transition functions depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{s}\times\Sigma_{c}$
\end_inset

 or on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{s}\otimes\Sigma_{c}$
\end_inset

 ?
 The former has the problem of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

who chooses
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

?
 The later says that the menu of current choices in intricately entangled with the external state of the external world ...
 and indeed it is.
 But just saying 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

oh it's the tensor product
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

oh it's entangled
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is glib.
 This needs to be articulated.
 I don't understand what this means.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 there's an issue with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

measure–preserving
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This seems correct if the agent to be described is a biological cell (eukaryote,
 prokaryote) and the measure is the baryon number.
 The cell contents are preserved,
 excluding ingestion of food,
 intake of water or ions.
 But for digital agents,
 the inside contains the world–model,
 and the complexity of that world model is generally increasing.
 If I think of the world model as some assembled sheaf of jigsaws,
 that assembly increases over time,
 so the measure cannot be the number of jigsaws,
 nor the number of connections.
 The measure can be something simpler,
 though:
 it can be just an ensemble.
 (A thermodynamic ensemble?!) The ensemble here is the analog of the mixed state in quantum:
 the measure allows us to track many 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

individuals
